segments.text: Cynthia says that the only way George will go is if we're going, because he doesn't like to travel.
And we enjoy being with one another.
It's very comfortable.
And so we made, I would say, a half a dozen trips together to China and Yugoslavia, through Italy, France.
And we generally rent a car together, or two cars, whatever the case may be.
And we have a lot of adventures.
And of course, in the process, we get into a town, I check out the restaurants.
And I have an instinct for it.
That's a good quality to have.
I took a walk through town.
I found a place around the corner that I think would be perfect.
And we haven't had too many bad meals that way.
I can tell by the menu, by the ambience.
Sometimes I can go in and talk to the proprietor, his shed looks clean and all, whatever the case may be.
So I'm his restaurant grazer.
That's good.
And we've had a lot of interest.
We went all through Sicily together.
And I realized maybe that wasn't a good choice, because taking George Mitchell with his wealth to Sicily is what the band has got us.
And on the other hand, nothing happened.
No problem.
No problem at all.
But at any rate, the Woodlands was full of excitement to me.
I saw it as an aesthetic accomplishment as well as a practical accomplishment about providing good living, good environment for families.
So as George went along, he would share his dream with me every step of the way.
Not that he saw my advice or some things I can't help with, you know, real estate matters and all that, but when he talked about having a research center and when he talked about
Park, and we talked about that, he would park those ideas to me just as a means of, I guess, using a council or a friend as a backboard, you know, and talk about it.
And his ideas were always exciting and far-reaching.
I never thought he would do the thing.
No, I knew he would do what he did in terms of Park, but his ambitions were so far-reaching
What do you see as the distinctive or unusual qualities of the Way?
It's more than this new community idea presented in that book, it seems to me.
What is special?
What's special about this place?
I don't think people, most people appreciate the fact that this is wonderful living.
Freedom from
Social insecurity, like we see in the big city.
I live in Chicago.
You have to be very careful walking down certain streets at night.
Chicago less so than New York or Los Angeles.
So you have that.
You have a perfect environment for children, I think.
It's a beautiful place to live.
The buys are fantastic.
The values are fantastic.
You have a man who is sincerely devoted
provided the best environment there is in the country.
It's like going into a restaurant, you've got the proprietor you can talk to.
And there's a direct communication in a way to George Mitchell, because he's patrolling the place all the time.
It's his baby.
He's very interested in everything.
And to me it's so incredible that George is so detail-minded.
I think I'm that way too.
But George, he's
He'll drive down some street, and if you see something wrong, he'll attend to it or call somebody.
He's on the premise.
He's not a remote entrepreneur.
So his very heart and spirit are in this place.
What about the research component in the Woodlands?
Is that something relatively new, or did you sense that that was developing early on also?
In other words, the integrated economic community seems to be...
Well, I have a feeling that I didn't quite appreciate it at the start, because I didn't realize how far he was going to go with it.
I knew what it was, and I knew it would be an important component here, because I was familiar with the gold triangle down at Duke, and I knew what they did.
And I was once called on to lecture there, and I got a little better penetration than most outsiders.
But I think he's done something that's so remarkable.
It's fraught with problems.
The problem is essentially that George is such a benevolent benefactor and that people feel, well, if they need money, George can do it.

That's really the big problem there, that it's so closely identified with the Woodlands and George Mitchell that the community takes the position, well, we really don't have to help it too much because it's George's baby and he can give the money.
And George continues to help them financially.
But on the other hand, he wants them to get themselves free from him, not because of the money, because he thinks it's good for their long-range future and thinks the community will embrace it.
Now, whether the community will ever do it adequately, because it's in the woodlands, is a question.
You also have a series of universities, each of which
has their own destiny in mind.
They favor Park.
On the other hand, they're mostly concerned about their own identification.
And I can see that.
In a way, they're in competition with each other.
But they don't realize.
I want to be very careful what I say, if it's a matter of record, not to cause any problems for George and his relationship.
No, I don't care.
I'll be very careful.
Early in my relationship with the Hertz Enterprise, and I worked on this, I realized something very important.
The licensees, some of the licensees were very upset that they had to handle referrals, calls for the rental of a car for other licensees.
You're living in Milwaukee.
You call the guy and you say, I need a car in Chicago tomorrow.
And he has to communicate with Chicago.
Some short-sighted licensees would say, hell, I don't get anything out of that.
Why should I give them any special attention?
Yet, the reason those licensees grew and prospered, became so enormous, was the Hertz program grew enormously.
They were able to attract a big subsidy advertising program from major car manufacturers.
They were advertised to such an extent that the guy in Milwaukee began to prosper.
He got a lot of business out of this cooperative effort.
Yet early in the game, he resisted it.
That's a pain in the ass for me to work on their problems.
I don't get anything out of it.
I keep the clerk busy all the time handling referrals to Miami, for example.
So I think the same thing applies here.

There has to be a tremendous amount of work by all the universities to make HAARC grow and become very important, as a result of which HAARC's umbrella will bring more research grants to the universities.
At least that's my assessment.
That's a difficult job.
Universities are very jealous of each other.
Yeah, well, I sensed that.
I ran a seminar yesterday where we had 16 people there, the heads of each of the disciplines.
And we talked about what the objectives were, what the problems were.
These were representatives from the universities?
Yes.
And it was a five-hour seminar.
And when I got through, I was totally exhausted.
I flopped in bed because I was on for five hours.
And it wasn't that I was talking for five hours.
I was dealing with each one.
There was confrontation a little bit.
It was friendly.
An exchange of ideas between these people.
A lot of the universities are very parochial.
They're very provincial.
It's like nothing exists outside of your borders.
Yeah.
And I sensed that here and there in that room.
And they sense a great deal of power within themselves.
A&M does, and Texas does, of course.

Well, I'm sure, you know, I remember I reminded myself of that McGraw-Hill ad where the guy's trying to sell something, and the executive's sitting in the chair and says, I don't know what you want, I don't know what you have to sell, I don't want any of it, you know?
That's it.
In a way, talking before that academic audience there yesterday,
I wondered if it was there.
I didn't sense it after a while, because I have some experience in warming up the audience and getting them to at least listen to me.
I don't know if they trusted me.
But when it was all over, they all stood up and applauded.
I guess that means something, I don't know.
It certainly does.
It certainly does, but they probably wouldn't.
Maybe it's Texas politeness.
If they just sat there and applauded, I would agree.
Well, they wanted to leave.
But one guy actually said, well, this is very interesting.
He said, but you didn't tell us anything we don't know.
Well, I know what I did, that I got them all to think together.
There were a number of people in the room who didn't know everything that they thought they knew.
And a number of people were very excited to ask me if I'd come back.
But one professional said, well, you didn't tell me anything I didn't know.
Well, that's happened to me a half a dozen times in my life.
People have said that to me.
And I'm always amused.
Because I don't know anything that they don't know.
It's just that what I do is package it.
And I put a discipline to it.
So anyway, along the lines, George and I have, I guess we've dreamed together.
And he exchanges ideas with me.
And sometimes I will then say, well, I think we ought to do this or that in terms of the communication factor to carry the message out.
Are we going to have a press conference?
Are we going to do this or that?
I would say for the last 10 or 15 years, I haven't really been heavily involved in the account, in the nuts and bolts of the account.
I'm a consultant, essentially.
And I'm an idea generator.
I'm a counsel.
I'm an advice giver.
What I do is unearth dramatic ideas from the stuff they already have, ways of presenting them.
And when I thought of Noguchi I knew that would bring all kinds of people here.
I wish we had it.
You know how much that Noguchi playground would be worth today as a piece of art?
I have no idea but I'm sure a lot.
probably ten, twenty million dollars, you know, and just a piece.
You took the components out, you could sell them.
I recently saw a fountain at the Pompidou Museum in Paris.
It would be perfect for the woodlands, and I took all kinds of pictures and sent them to George, and George tells me, he's translating them now and giving them to his designers.
Whether he'll ever do it or not, it may be too expensive, but it's a fountain that has, a large fountain that has revolving pieces of art.
in the style of, you know Ricky St. Paul, have you ever seen him work?
No.
You know the Michelin figure with the pumped up balloon?
Well she does figures like that.
And she did some figures that are revolving in this fountain.
They're kind of childlike large blown up figures.
And I think that would be a tremendous joy.
But you know, a lot of these ideas that I developed
are beyond budget.
The Woodlands isn't making a lot of money, which it isn't.
Can't spend that kind of money yet, but they will someday, some of those things.
So I keep looking at things.
Why does George Mitchell do this?
I interviewed him and tried to ask basically the same question.
I'm not sure I got an answer.
What does he do what?
Why does he do the Woodlands?
What is it?
What's the motivation?
To build a city?
Because he...
He just likes to do things.
You know, I'm really trying to understand the individual.
This is his creative monument.
The other is a business, you know.
Yeah, this is not a business.
No, it's a creative monument to George, to a man's vision to build what he considers a perfect city.
And George has rationalized that the urban communities really are in the state of decay.
Yeah, right.
He said that.
You go around the country and see all these communities.
You go to Hammond, Indiana, or Gary, Indiana, or Indianapolis.
Even Chicago itself has a terrible problem with its downtown and is spending a lot of money trying to revive it.
Living conditions are such that it's very difficult for people.
Cost of homes, all that kind of crime, schooling, all that kind.
Is there anything comparable to this in your travels and experiences that you would really relate or correlate?
Well, the one that's built
Baltimore.
It's called Reston.
It's said to be capital, but I haven't seen it.
You mean Columbia?
You mean Columbia you're talking about?
Yeah, Columbia.
It's the name of the company that built it, Reston.
Yeah, Reston built it.
The community is called Columbia.
I haven't seen it, but I understand it's nothing like this.
It's a planned community that's successful.
George has developed the most successful village of this sort
that was sponsored by the government.
It was a hug.
The only one that really survived.
And it will survive.
And luckily, George had an energy company that could help subsidize it as it went through the maturation period.
And George, there are some people who are naysayers.
Members of his own board said, George, you're nuts.
What are you doing this for?
Energy companies making all these profits, and you're pouring it into this thing.
Well, I think someday probably Mitchell Energy will spin off either Mitchell Energy or the Woodlands.
And the Woodlands is going to be worth a fortune, a tremendous fortune.
This is a piece of property.
I don't know what it's carrying.
So you think it's really coming into its own.
It's in the developmental stage, too, basically.
Yes.
Well, there are 28,000 people living there now.
And when I tell people that George acquired 85,000 acres,
in ten years in eight hundred different transactions.
I'm not sure of the exact figures, but that's my recollection.
Oh, it's your clock, I think.

Yeah, and the way he did his persistence, his dogged persistence in getting this done and pulling it together and hiring Roy Ferreira, you know, for the landscaping and all that, the terrain, and great architects.
And I'm just amazed that he
that he can do so many things at one time, remember them, give attention to detail.
You know, I go to the Mardi Gras down in Galveston.
I go in almost every year except one, I guess.
And he patrols the streets and he sees the exhibits are right, and you know, all kinds of things.
You know, we've interviewed some twenty people in the Woodlands, and three or four times now, during our interview, the phone
rang and George Mitchell was on the phone to talk to this individual, who had no direct relationship at all, I wouldn't have thought.
But that was a good indicator in my mind of the close contact.
Well, he remembers almost everything you ever said to him or anything anybody else has ever said to him.
He still finds time to give attention to his children.
He still finds time to play tennis every day.
He plays a damn good game of tennis.
You ever seen him play?
No, I haven't, but I've heard.
He's as good as they can.
At his age, I would say he's a top-ranked tennis player.
He's a great outdoorsman.
He loves to fish and hunt and all that kind of stuff.
Our greatest fun has been as he's turned me into an outdoorsman.
I'm a city dweller.
I don't know how to fish.
He's taught me how to fish.
He puts the shrimp
on my hook, and he throws it in the water, and I pull it in, and he takes it off.
He calls me the great white hunter.
I used to go out to Cook's Ranch to get some deer once in a while.
And I'm rated as blind by the Air Force.
I was given a certified disability discharge at the base of my bad eyesight.
And when I fire, a deer drops.
And I'm convinced they hang the deer up.
And when I fire, they drop it.
I've never missed.
And my wife and I are in the blind there, and I'm ready to shoot.
She said, don't shoot.
That's such a beautiful deer.
And the deer drops when you don't.
Once I fired, and I almost cried because the deer ran off.
And I said, oh, I may have wounded it.
And the ranger said, what happened?
Did you go into the wood after him?
I said, I went as far as I could go.
Well, they were very worried about it.
Because you never miss a shot.
And I said, no, I missed that one.
The next day we went in deep in the woods and the deer had run in and died.
Is that right?
Yeah.
That's the only one I missed, I thought.
Because we lost the meat.
We lost the animal.
We destroyed an animal, unfortunately.
And I've been wild turkey shooting.
Oh, I once went...
white goose hunting with George, you know, in the southwest or somewhere.
Yeah, so he's given me that part of his life, which I appreciate.
An insight into him, we went, we lay out crab pots in the bay, and we went out one night about four o'clock when I first arrived, and we put out these crab pots.
We got out about a half mile, and the motor conked out.
Now, I said to George, we'll both get in the water and we'll pull the boat in, because it's only six feet there or something like that.
He said, oh no, I'll do it.
You stay in the boat.
So if you're going to visualize the picture, George has a rope around his neck.
I'm in the boat with one oar.
All we have is one oar.
And I'm a half-assed singer, and I'm singing all the Russian songs.
That's a memorable picture.
George pulls the boat in for about a
It took us about three quarters of an hour to get to shore.
He's in the water pulling it.
And the mosquitoes, he had a better deal.
The mosquitoes were biting me.
That's probably why he got in the water.
He knew what he was doing.
When I got to shore, I almost passed out.
I was so bitten.
But it was a funny sight, this processional of this great tycoon pulling at the rope, and I'm in there.

If there is a, what do you think the public perception is of the Woodlands, or should be, if it is, in other words, where this meeting is in terms of what people believe it to be and what it is, is that pretty well now in conjunction?
Well, I think people in Houston, for example, which is, the Houston area is their best market, are beginning to appreciate
I say, I don't know what the percentage is, but I say there's an increased perception, increased appreciation of the woodlands, as far as I can tell by talking to people that I meet from this area.
I come in here and I have friends here.
At the start it used to be considered Mitchell's Folly, you know, who's going to move out there?
But now these things that are occurring, this
Expressway that's coming here.
What's the name of the expressway?
Hard Toll Road.
Hard Toll Road, you know, which makes it so easy to get out here.
The transportation system.
The pavilion is a stroke of genius, you know.
There's a lot of people who come out here who never visited this place before.
So I would say there's an increased perception, which was hampered somewhat by the economic environment.
I'd say it wouldn't be further along.
And yet, all during this past three or four years, they've done very well, as I understand it, on a comparative basis with what some of the real estate has done.
And there's everything here you could want.
Now, as more and more things are added here, the school system and other things, and more jobs, and the scientists out here, there'll be more people who want to live out here.
So I think it's going to be an enormously successful place.
And then, of course, when the homeowners feel that they own their villages and exercise more care in the preservation of those villages and the maintenance.
Do you think those people will be able to sustain the woodland's aura or character once, in other words, in this weaning process?
There is a tension, apparently.
Well, it would be to their advantage to do so.
It certainly would now.
I've been through a similar situation.
I once did a consulting job for a place called the Nichols.
There's a village, a cluster of villages that's similar, run by the J.C. Nichols Company out of Kansas City.
They were the developers of the original shopping center.
First major drive-in shopping center in the country.
And it's still a big and viable economic real estate empire.

And what happened was, as the villages, each of these clusters took over ownership, proprietary ownership of their villages, they wanted to make certain changes, which distressed the J.C. Nichols Company.
And they began to agitate for things.

There are problems that occur when those clusters take over ownership in terms of what they want to do, what they don't want to do, and what their attitude is toward the major benefactor, which is the Woodlands Corporation.
I can anticipate all kinds of things happening in the future.
But nothing that's injurious or will cause anything to happen here that will limit this place.
And little by little, George is adding exciting elements here.
To be able to have the PGA here, which is fantastic.
And to have Frank Sinatra sing here, which is incredible.
Were you out here for that opening?
No, no.
No, we've heard about it.
He gave an incredible concert.
He's a man that's not in his prime anymore.
But he's a great showman.
All kinds of things happening here.
So by starting my life all over, I would be living down here, no question about it, because everything that's here I love.
What I don't see is a good place to eat yet.
And I don't see movie theaters that are as convenient as I like them.
Ultimately, there has to be something more of a cultural nature with people, legitimate
maybe a repertory group here or something like that, but that will come.
How about university-type complexes or educational?

Terribly important, sure, because if you had a university out here and you can participate in the cultural life of the university and mix with some of those people who are living here, it makes it a fuller life.
I spent a lot of time in Palm Springs, and I wouldn't spend the time there if it weren't for the fact
We have a cultural center, and we have legitimate plays come in, and the symphonies, visiting symphonies, and all kinds of movie theaters if you want to go.
But I think that's going to come.
And I know George will see it in his lifetime.
It's going to take another 25 years, I would say, for the kind of maturation that I'm talking about.
Yeah, I've heard that number used quite a lot.
I see.
It's a long-range picture.
But look what they've got already.
That's right.
Incredible.
One of the problems of the woodlands, I've addressed it a number of times, and I keep working on things over the years.
If I agitate enough, ultimately somebody does something about it, because they get tired of hearing me talk about it.
When you drive into the woodlands, you don't see the woodlands.
You start on the expressway drive in, and you say, what the hell is this?
It's a lot of trees.
And you see there's a name identification.
And you say, well, do I want to see Grogan's Mill or whatever it is?
I don't know what it is.
Where's the pavilion?
How do I find it?
And all that stuff.
So I've been pushing for kind of a map, a picture map, like Life magazine.
You open it up, and there'd be a corollary number on a post, which is number one, and the map shows you what's behind the tree.
Yeah, a walking tour.
A walking tour of the place.
See, now, they've gone so far as they're doing a picture book now.
But that isn't what I have in mind.
Maybe the picture book will suffice.
People can get around.
But I want a numbered walking tour or auto tour of this place.
When you're able to look at it, if you're just to cut off the, go through the top and see this place, it's incredible what's here.
But I see the gorgeous homes here that people are able to get.
Of course, it's a double-edged sword, too.
One of the things that I sense some of the residents, you know, we were talking earlier about whether the local associations will pick up the gauntlet and continue.
I see them as actually, in some ways,
jealous of the good things about the Woodlands, maybe even the Woodlands Corporation has been.
Because they've really bought into the ideas here.
That's why they're here.
But I've lived here since 73 and have driven down to Houston all the time.
And frankly, the Woodlands, as you said, was to me a wall of trees on the right side of I-45 as you drove down.
And it had no meaning whatsoever.
But at the same token, were I living here,

You know, there's some mixed feelings about, do I want a walking tour where individuals, you know, from elsewhere, you know, where the woodlands becomes a tourist kind of event for its continued growth.
You live here now?
No.
Oh, you did live here?
No.
College Station.
College Station is where I'm from.
I live up here in Coliseum.
Well, you know, it's the same problem we're dealing with, the universities versus Harkin.
If the people who live in the woodlands realize that if this community grows, they'll get more things here, they'll get that movie theater right in here.
They'll get the shopping centers and all that.
So you have to take a long view of the welfare.
And my feeling is that if more people came and saw this place, more people would want to come and live here.
It's that simple.
I've always, I like the title, I guess, The Machine in the Garden.
And I see that as one of the possible tensions of the future in the woodlands.
Too much development.
Of course, the kind of development they're trying to do is trying to tone that down a little bit.
Too much business, if you will, that might disturb the garden aspects of the woodlands as one of the futures.
They don't want any infringement on their privacy.
No, that's right.
Can you have it both?
Can you have progress and can you have progress?
Look, I live in condominiums in Chicago and in Palm Springs.
And there's some things I have to do as kind of a social enterprise.
I have to do as an owner of a condominium apartment or home.
I've got to live with my neighbors.
I don't like the fact that the pool is filled with children on holidays.
I don't like the fact the neighbor across the street has a dog that barks once in a while.
or there's another neighbor who's visited by a relative with a recreational vehicle, and it's parked in the street, some things I don't like.
If they're against the condominium rules, I protest it and get it stopped.
But if it's just a violation of what I consider my privacy, I either have to live with it or I have to move.
And the same thing here.
If you're living here, if you want the place to offer you all the good things you want in life,
You have to participate in the growth of this community and the recognition of this community.
I think that's the key.
And apparently the Woodlands has done a good job, I think, of organizing such that there is participation.
Well, the infrastructure itself.
The infrastructure itself is a conservative instrument.
It maintains, well, the natural environment.
That's a sacrosanct.
Yes, sure.
In fact, they're moving.
Bill Kendrick, who's responsible for the grounds here,
One thing to ask myself is, is there, in fact, a set of rules, regulations?
Has the things which you have developed been codified?
And he says, no, but we're going to do that.
He says, we've arrived at the point where we can do that.
And I think that infrastructure is what's going to preserve the integrity of the ruins, for want of a better term, through the stages of growth.
I think it's an exciting project, and it's true to its principles.
And as long as George stays alive, it'll be true.
He's got a son on the board now, and his son probably will carry on those principles for the years.
And George, of course, has always maintained control over the corporation, so nobody can take it away from him.
Not from the standpoint of preserving his wealth so much, but preserving his control.
You know, we talk about proxy fights and all that.
Can't do that with Mitchell Energy, you know.
What the hell is he is when a guy owns more than 60% of the company?
And, you know, you talk to George about wealth, he never is concerned about his own wealth.
I've never heard him talk along those lines.
God, I just lost $2 million today or something like that.
He doesn't do that like most executives.
That's an abstraction to him.
It's a benchmark when he has to look at it.
What he's mostly concerned is going ahead with his dreams.
And that includes, of course, the enormous job.
Have you looked at Galveston recently, what he's done there?
Yeah, I spent a lot of time there.
Yeah.
Well, it's enormous what they've done.
Each year I come down, there's something new.
The restaurant across the way, I forget the name of it.
God, you can't get in the place.
And that Irish pub, can't get in the place.
his vision and building, you know, bringing the Mardi Gras back.
Yeah, that worked.
Yeah, great idea.
I guess the other arena that I am concerned with here is the art.
I keep pushing the concept of having more art for aesthetic appreciation and also ultimately it should be an artistic adventure to come out here, you know, just to look at these.
famous sculpture.
One of the best things he has here was done by a friend of mine that George and I visited in Rome.
We went to his studio and George commissioned.
It was Robert Cook.
I don't know if you've seen his piece.
Which one is it?
It's the one where the young man stands on the shoulder.
It's a beautiful piece.
I have a big collection of that man.
George saw it when he was with me.
Next thing I knew he commissioned it.
I didn't even know it.
until it was erected here.
And he sprung a surprise on me.
He had Bob Cook do it.
It's a lovely piece.
I think it's the best pleat piece of the woodlands, frankly.
You ought to have more pieces like that, that are a fine piece of art, that are expressive.
And I feel that there ought to be a universal, consistent theme of the collection of art.
See, if I were starting fresh, I would have nothing but Southwestern art here.
by great Southwestern artists and sculptors.
At this point, I feel that the collection is kind of random.
Somebody saw something, and they bought it, and they like it.
It's a little apocalyptic.
Yeah.
I really feel that what I would have started with either Southwestern artists or great American artists, but this would lend itself to Southwestern artists.
Or a lot of Mexican art, Zuniga's and people like that.
I used to go to the University out there to see those murals.
I've not seen those.
Fantastic, yeah.
There will be ultimately stuff here like that.
I would certainly enhance the quality and the appeal of the literature.
Well, I think we've pretty well covered the... My God.
What time did we start?
Well, about 9.
An hour and a half.
Well, that's pretty good.
Well, this is a big treat for me to have somebody listen to me.
Who wants to listen to me for half an hour?
I'd like to know more about your public relations business and some interviews.
